            "section": "Background"
        },
        {
            "text": "In the context of interstitial lung disease (ILD) associated to connective tissue diseases, lung ultrasound has been proposed as an integration to CT for diagnosis [10] and follow-up monitoring [11] ; in this chronic setting, different quantitative approaches based on the total number of visualized B-lines in all the intercostal spaces have been applied to monitor ILD progression [12] and evaluate timing of radiological follow-up [13] . However, how to use lung ultrasound to monitor the response to Open Access *Correspondence: silvia.mongodi@libero.it treatment in acute respiratory failure associated to rheumatic diseases is still unclear. We describe a prolonged ultrasound monitoring in acute exacerbation of ILD associated to connective tissue disease.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 164,
